\begin_layout Section
Fixed Costs
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Refer to the graphs at the end of the Section Notes.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a production technology that produces one output, one input, and
 a production function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(\cdot)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(\cdot)<0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that a production function will have an explicit form, while the
 transformation function will have an implicit form.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume further that the cost function associated with this production technolog
y is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
c(q)=\frac{1}{2}q^{2}+q+3.\label{eq:cost func}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do you see that there is fixed cost component to this production technology?
 What is the fixed cost? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Is the fixed cost sunk? Note that this is an assumption that you will have
 to make.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Recall that we were able to derive the cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\vec{\omega},q)$
\end_inset

 from plugging the solutions to the cost minimization problem (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

CMP
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{z}^{*}=\vec{z}(\vec{\omega},q)$
\end_inset

, back into the objective function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\omega}\cdot\vec{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{*}=c(\vec{\omega},q)=\vec{\omega}\cdot\vec{z}(\vec{\omega},q)$
\end_inset

.
 When working with cost functions of the form found in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cost func"

\end_inset

, we are assuming that the input prices, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\omega}$
\end_inset

, are fixed, or that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(q)=c(\bar{\vec{\omega}},q)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the cost function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cost func"

\end_inset

, we can calculate the marginal cost of production at 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 units:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
MC(q)=c'(q)=q+1\]

\end_inset

, and the average cost of producing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 units:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
AC(q)=\frac{c(q)}{q}=\frac{1}{2}q+1+\frac{3}{q}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

