\begin_layout Section
Partial Equilibrium
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We call it partial equilibrium because we focus on one good and a composite
 commodity (all other goods).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Model (and Notation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Consumers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 consumers each with the following utility function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
u_{i}(m_{i},x_{i})=m_{i}+\phi_{i}(x_{i})\]

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'(\cdot)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi''(\cdot)<0$
\end_inset

.
 Each individual has endowment of the numeraire good 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 and no endowment of good 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The price vector for the two goods 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}=[p_{m},p_{x}]=[1,p]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an equilibrium, all consumers will be maximizing their utilities subject
 to their respective budget constraints.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Producers (Firms)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 producers each of which has a cost function, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}(q_{j})$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that MWG may use the more general notation 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 to be consistent with the production plan vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is measured in terms of units of the numeraire good.
 Producers (or firms) use the numeraire good, which is supplied by the consumers
 (recall that consumers are endowed with the numeraire good) in exchange
 for good 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and transforms them into the output good 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 which is denoted in the context of the firm as 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note also that the firms themselves are owned by the consumers.
 The ownership share of consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{ij}$
\end_inset

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}\theta_{ij}=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is also important to remember the budget constraint of the consumer's
 utility maximization problem must also take into consideration this ownership
 share of firms.
 Therefore, the total wealth available to consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
w_{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{J}\theta_{ij}\Pi_{j}(p^{*})\]

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{j}(p^{*})$
\end_inset

 is equal to the profit of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 at price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Market Clears at equilibrium price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It must be the case that at the equilibrium price, 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

, the total amount of good 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 demanded and supplied must be equal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{J}q_{j}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Partial Equilibrium Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is themarket equi.
 in the following case: 100 consumers, all with 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(m_{i},x_{i})=m_{i}+\ln x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and endowment 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=\frac{1}{100}w_{m}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}=[p_{m},p_{x}]=[1,p]$
\end_inset

; and one firm, with cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $c(q)=5q^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall i$
\end_inset

 the ownership share 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{ij=1}=\frac{1}{100}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Producers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each producer solves the PMP (in our problem, we only have one firm) to
 derive the net supply function of good 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 In short, we are looking for the optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\max_{q}\Pi(p)=pq-c(q)=pq-5q^{2}\]

\end_inset

.
 The FOCs result in:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial\Pi(q^{*})}{\partial q}=p-10q^{*}=0\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}\Pi(q^{*})}{\partial q^{2}}=-10<0$
\end_inset

, so we're at a maximum.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and so the supply function can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
q^{*}(p)=\frac{p}{10}\label{eq:supply}\end{equation}

\end_inset

, and the optimal profit function is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Pi^{*}(p)=\frac{p^{2}}{10}-\frac{5p^{2}}{100}=\frac{p^{2}}{20}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Consumers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each consumer solves his or her own utility maximization problem subject
 to a wealth constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\max_{m_{i},x_{i}}u_{i}(m_{i},x_{i})=m_{i}+\ln x_{i}\, s.t.\, m_{i}+px_{i}\leq\frac{w_{m}}{100}+\frac{\Pi^{*}(p)}{100}\]

\end_inset

, where we know that at the optimum, the constraint will bind.
 This is important since we don't have to resort to the Lagrangian method.
 We can rewrite the problem as an unconstrained maximization:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Do we have to worry about corner solutions? Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 is allowed to be negative (meaning that the consumer can borrow) and that
 the Inada condition for the non-numeraire good applies.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\max_{x_{i}}u_{i}(x_{i})=-px_{i}+\frac{w_{m}}{100}+\frac{\Pi^{*}(p)}{100}+\ln x_{i}\]

\end_inset

.
 The FOCs result in:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\partial u(x_{i}^{*})}{\partial x_{i}}=-p+\frac{1}{x_{i}^{*}}=0\Rightarrow x_{i}^{*}(p)=\frac{1}{p}.\label{eq:demand}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note how the ownership share does not enter into the FOC.
 Remember that we're using a quasilinear utility function, so there are
 no wealth effects.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Markets Clear at the Equilibrium Price 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since supply must equal demand at the equilibrium price, we have from equations
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:supply"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:demand"

\end_inset

 that the following equation must hold at the equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
q^{*}(p^{*})=\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}^{*}(p^{*})\Rightarrow\frac{p^{*}}{10}=\frac{100}{p^{*}}\Rightarrow p^{*}=10\sqrt{10}\approx31.6\label{eq:market clear}\end{equation}

\end_inset

, which means that the equilibrium level of good 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that is consumed is equal to:
\begin_inset Formula \[
q^{*}(31.6)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}x_{i}^{*}(31.6)=\sqrt{10}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

